title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>(1) Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi \colon  R\to (R/I)\times (R/J)]]></fr:tex> be the mapping such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi (x)=(x+I,x+J)]]></fr:tex> for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  R]]></fr:tex>. Its kernel is <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\cap  J]]></fr:tex>. Then by the <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-0018.xml"
addr="ra-0018"
title="First Isomorphism Theorem for Rings">first isomorphism theorem</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi '\colon  R/(I\cap  J)\to (R/I)\times (R/J)]]></fr:tex> is injective because it has a trivial kernel. We need to show it is surjective.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(u+I,v+J)\in (R/I)\times (R/J)]]></fr:tex>, we want to find <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  R]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi (x)=(u+I,v+J)]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  I]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  J]]></fr:tex> be such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a+b=1]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x=va+ub]]></fr:tex>, so we can check <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi '(x)=(a+A,b+B)]]></fr:tex>. We find
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {align*}x &\equiv  ub\bmod {I}\\ &\equiv  (1-a)u\bmod {I}\\ &\equiv  u\bmod {I}\end {align*}]]></fr:tex>
and similarly <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\equiv  v\bmod {B}]]></fr:tex> as desired.</fr:p>
<fr:p>(2) Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> are comaximal, there exists <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  I]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  J]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a+b=1]]></fr:tex>. We want to show <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\cap  J\subseteq  I\cdot  J]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  I\cap  J]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x=x\cdot 1=xa+xb]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[xa\in  JI]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[xb\in  IJ]]></fr:tex>, hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  I\cdot  J]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>We see <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\cap  J\supseteq  I\cdot  J]]></fr:tex> obviously.</fr:p>
