title="Ring">Ring</fr:link>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-0024.xml"
addr="ra-0024"
title="Comaximal ideals">comaximal</fr:link> <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-0011.xml"
addr="ra-0011"
title="Ideal">two-sided ideals</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>. Then
<fr:ol><fr:li>the map
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[R/(I\cap  J)\to  (R/I)\times (R/J)]]></fr:tex>
defined by sending <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\mapsto (x+I,x+J)]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-000X.xml"
addr="ra-000X"
title="Ring Isomorphism">Ring Isomorphism</fr:link>; and</fr:li>
<fr:li>furthermore if we write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\cdot  J=\langle \{ab\in  R\mid  a\in  I,b\in  J\}\rangle ]]></fr:tex> for the two-sided ideal generated by products of elements of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\cdot  J=I\cap  J]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li></fr:ol></fr:p>
 
   
